OK, a few more questions that I think I know the answer to, but I want to avoid any blatantly rookie mistakes.For primary fermentation, I have three places in the house where I can store the fermenter: -An upstairs room that will be mid to high 60s in the spring, fall and winter, mid to high 70s in the summer-A downstairs room that will be high 60s to low 70s in the summer, potentially dropping to low to mid 60s at night in the winter-The basement which is probably low to mid 60s all year long, maybe dipping slightly colder in the winter.I figure that I want the ambient temp of whatever room I have my fermentation happening in to be high 60s to low 70s, so I'm thinking that during the summer I should ferment in the downstairs room, and then store bottles in the basement after carbination, and during the winter I should ferment in the upstairs room. Am I over thinking this? I'm trying to avoid ice baths and heating pads. Reading over the kit instructions online, they don't really seem to be concerned with ambient room temperature to the extent that you guys are.
kmeeks
Ars Tribunus Militum
