Tribus: Iowa City, IA
Registered: Jan 18, 2001Posts: 2510
Posted: Sat Apr 07, 2012 9:05 am
Generally speaking yes, ales are best fermented in the high 60's to low 70's. That said, do consider the type of beers and adjust accordingly. For example, Belgian and Hefeweizen yeasts like higher temps than Irish stout or American Wheat yeasts. Were I doing a quad or hefe in the summer I'd put them in the upstairs room, would ferment a stout in the downstairs room, and a Kolsch in the basement. Wyeast and White Labs both list temperature ranges for each strain on their website, just check them when your planning a given batch.:edit: That said, don't overthink it (something I can be guilty of). There's absolutely nothing wrong with sticking with the mid-range temperature, just that playing with temps can accentuate the flavors. The banana/clove flavors in a hefe come out stronger in a higher temperature fermentation, but you'll still find the classic notes if fermented at 70 vs 78. In general higher fermentation temperatures for ale yeasts tend to lead to greater ester production, lower can lead to cleaner more neutral profiles. It can be fun to do the same exact recipe and expose it to different environments to see exactly how it's different.
DJ Immortal
