DJ Immortal wrote:Frennzy wrote:DJ Immortal wrote:Quote:and never pitch yeast and such high temps, you'll get off flavours, assuming your yeast survives.A lot of times I just leave my hot wort in its bucket and let it sit all night and pitch yeast in the morning.A lot of the FAQs I've seen say to wait to get it below 80*; should I try for just under 80 or more like 70, knowing it'll eventually stabilize around the surrounding temperature?Don't you people have immersion chillers? If you don't, you can make one for a few bucks and a trip to your local Home Depot.Like dak says, there's other stuff higher on the priority list.Such as? Presumably you have your carboy(s). You obviously have a boiling pot and a heat source. I'm guessing you already have appropriate stoppers, tubing, and cleaners.If you stop and think about it, the single longest time component of homebrewing is cooling the wort. A chiller can *greatly* reduce that amount of time. How much is your time worth? Further, every minute your wort is sitting there cooling, you're exposing it to more potential infection/corruption (what word am I thinking of here?...basically I'm imagining things like fur, skin cells, dust, bugs, etc. landing in your wort)It just seems like such a simple thing that is a fantastic time saver. I made one back in 2001 or so (granted copper has gone up a lot since then) and it was literally less than 20 dollars and 20 minutes. I wrapped 3/8" tubing around a 3lb coffee can, and used hose clamps to attach rubber tubing to each end. On one end of the tubing, and I used a hose clamp and an adapter to connect it to a waterbed filler adapter, which screwed into my sink faucet. I could chill a 5 gallon boil in less than 10 minutes.Also, I'd bet if you go to a local homebrew club chapter meeting, you'll be able to find someone who has a spare. (either they sized up to 15 gallon batches, or moved on to a cold plate.)
