Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Tribus: 1NeJ69eo4aGGNoVwCAZ7nNy3GMYMGC1DSm
Registered: Oct 11, 2003Posts: 3174
Posted: Wed Apr 18, 2012 8:51 am
dak wrote:Additional question: The only single tube bender I can find is a $4 3/8" bender from Ace. Every other store only sells sets. Can I use a 3/8" bender to bend 1/4" tubing?So, Tube benders...I didn't use one. 3/8" would not work on 1/4".You should get your tube in a coil with some space at it's center. If you basically place your mold cylinder (be it a smaller pot, or what have you) and tighten the coil around the mold, you should basically have no issue. The touchiest part is getting the input and output arms up and pointed out. Larger radius turns should be used where possible. Not strictly NecessaryIf you can get your hands on some scrap solid core wire, or get ~1 foot of 3 conductor 14 guage Romex (should be ~$1/ft) and strip it to bare copper, use the wire to space the coils and add support to the in/out arms. I'd clean the wire with a scrubby, but it otherwise is fine for this application.EDIT: One last thing. Make the input the top of the coil. Since this is the coolest water and the hottest wort, it promotes even cooling and helps prevent stratification of hot wort on top and cold on bottom.
